                  <additions>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="a1">
                           <desc>
                              <locus target="#61v" facs="063"/> A small black cross marks the midpoint of the Psalms</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a2">
                           <desc>
                          Overlooked words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#6r #18r #24v #26r #44r #46r #50v" facs="007 019 026 027 045 047 052"/>, etc.);
                          and overlooked lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#25v #34v #35r #40v #43v #45v #50r" facs="027 036 042 045 047 051"/>, etc.);
                          and in the upper margin with a symbol (+) marking the location where the text is to be inserted
                          (<locus target="#98v" facs="100"> f. 98v, line 7 and </locus><locus target="#165r" facs="166"> f. 165r, line 5</locus>)
                        </desc>
                        </item>

                        <item xml:id="e1">
                           <desc>
                              <locus target="#ir(ecto)" facs="001"/> blank</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e2">
                           <desc>
                          The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate
                          aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe completes the line
                          of text above the end of the line (throughout).
                        </desc>
                        </item>
                    </list>


